In [8]:
# Defining dictionary of replacements for WindGustDir column
replace_WindGustDir = {
    'SSE': 'SE',
    'WSW': 'SW',
    'SSW': 'SW',
    'WNW': 'NW',
    'ENE': 'NE',
    'ESE': 'SE',
    'NNW': 'NW',
    'NNE': 'NE',
}

#iterate through 'WindGustDir' and replace incorrect values
for value, row in df.iterrows():
    for incorrect_value, correct_value in replace_WindGustDir.items():
        if row['WindGustDir'] == incorrect_value:
            df.at[value, 'WindGustDir'] = correct_value

Fillin missing values with Mean for numerical columns or Mode for categorical columns¶

In [19]:
numerical_columns = ['MinTemp', 'MaxTemp', 'Rainfall','WindGustSpeed', 'WindSpeed9am', 'WindSpeed3pm', 'Humidity9am', 
                     'Humidity3pm', 'Pressure9am', 'Pressure3pm', 'Temp9am', 'Temp3pm']
for col in numerical_columns:
    df[col].fillna(value=np.mean(df[col]), inplace = True)
In [20]:
categorical_columns = ['Location','WindGustDir','WindDir9am','WindDir3pm', 'RainToday']
for col in categorical_columns:
    df[col].fillna(df[col].mode()[0], inplace = True)

Determining the high cardinality in each categorical variable¶

In [24]:
#creating dictionary to store the cardinality of each categorical variable
cardinality_dict = {}

# Use forloop for the categorical columns and calculate cardinality
for col in categorical_columns:
    unique_counts = df[col].nunique()
    cardinality_dict[col] = unique_counts
    
#Print the cardinality for each categorical column
for col, cardinality in cardinality_dict.items():
    print(f"{col}: {cardinality} unique categories")

# Drop column that we're solving for
X_train = train.drop(columns = 'RainTomorrow')
X_test = test.drop(columns = 'RainTomorrow')

y_test = test.RainTomorrow
In [108]:
# Fit into Logistic Regression model
log = LogisticRegression(max_iter = 100)

pred = log.predict(X_test)
print(classification_report(y_true = y_test, y_pred = pred))
